{"id":14881629,"mediaExerciseId":"8d3fc3a8-18d9-4e38-bf8e-94074f7deb3c","exerciseName":"3","chapterName":"18","chapterTitle":"Short-Term Finance and Planning","groupId":612437,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":631,"solutions":[{"id":5676223,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we must label the provided transactions of Holly Corporation as either a source or use of cash.\n\nLet's first briefly define and know the difference between cash use and cash sources.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":136,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/38dc008580d5811ce0183c38b120f965/1e032fccfe4bc43d1ce4b7c4dd5f9f3c/lateximg_large.png","width":1004},"regular":{"height":70,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/38dc008580d5811ce0183c38b120f965/1e032fccfe4bc43d1ce4b7c4dd5f9f3c/lateximg.png","width":503}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"A **cash source** is any activity that generates cash for the business, while on the other hand, **cash use** is any company activity that expends its cash.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":99,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/38dc008580d5811ce0183c38b120f965/2940c621f0e1d4104565213bf3ca1ee7/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":50,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/21/38dc008580d5811ce0183c38b120f965/2940c621f0e1d4104565213bf3ca1ee7/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Next, Let's now label each of the given transactions as either cash source or use.\n\na. Cash dividends payment:\n\n **Use**: When dividends are paid to shareholders, retained earnings decrease, and the company expends cash for its dividends declaration.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":179,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/18/38dc008580d5811ce0183c38b120f965/735330cf4692160bb22940bcb3a5c083/lateximg_large.png","width":1018},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/18/38dc008580d5811ce0183c38b120f965/735330cf4692160bb22940bcb3a5c083/lateximg.png","width":510}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"b. Increase in account payable:\n\n**Source**: An increase in accounts payable may indicate an increase in assets, but no corresponding outflow of cash exists since this is an obligation that the company can pay over time.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/18/38dc008580d5811ce0183c38b120f965/09e15696304bb7df3876d070ec10d051/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/18/38dc008580d5811ce0183c38b120f965/09e15696304bb7df3876d070ec10d051/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"c. Purchase of fixed assets:\n\n**Use**: The balance of cash has decreased from the purchase of fixed assets, increasing the company's operating capacity.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":103,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/18/38dc008580d5811ce0183c38b120f965/b9c5c1f3271af019ac5fe2e1de6942de/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/18/38dc008580d5811ce0183c38b120f965/b9c5c1f3271af019ac5fe2e1de6942de/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"d. Increase in inventories:\n\n**Use**: The payment of inventories resulted in an outflow of cash, but the purchase has increased the total assets of the company","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":103,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/12/38dc008580d5811ce0183c38b120f965/a689979db361a3827f7b1d1f7425c19f/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/12/38dc008580d5811ce0183c38b120f965/a689979db361a3827f7b1d1f7425c19f/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"e. Decrease in long-term liabilities:\n\n**Use**: Payment of liabilities reduces the balance of cash but this reduces the financial risk to the company.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":103,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/12/38dc008580d5811ce0183c38b120f965/bfb50453792dcd014b34223584067763/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/11/12/38dc008580d5811ce0183c38b120f965/bfb50453792dcd014b34223584067763/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":7}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"4dd743f7-7159-4f72-8812-cfcdaee751b7","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":7},{"id":6402948,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we will annotate each question if it a source or use of cash and relate the effects on the cash balance of the firm.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Cash-increasing activities are a source of cash, and cash-reducing activities are the use of cash. This means that an increase in long-term liabilities and/or capital or/and short-term liabilities will lead to an increase in cash, and a decrease in fixed assets and/or other short-term assets will lead to an increase in cash.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"**(a)** **Application or Usage of cash:** To pay the dividend, the cash balance was reduced by $200.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"**(b)** **Origin or source of cash:** If the sales exceeded on current liabilities lending could be auctioned for profit, the cash position enhanced by $500.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"**(c) Application and usage of cash.** To pay again for capital expenditures, the cash balance was reduced by $900.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"**(d) Implementation and usage of cash**. The un-invested cash was reduced by $625 to cover the increased product availability.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"**(e) Application and usage of cash**. The capital account was reduced by $1,200 to expect to be paid for loan atonement.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":7}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"67390f8c-be04-496e-8719-a60ecfc434d3","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":7}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881630,"exerciseName":"4","page":631,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"41ded766-1bfd-4359-9be3-005b41225570","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-18-critical-thinking-questions-4-41ded766-1bfd-4359-9be3-005b41225570"},{"id":14881631,"exerciseName":"5","page":631,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"812ed3b9-af82-438f-805c-eaab16fe1df5","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-18-critical-thinking-questions-5-812ed3b9-af82-438f-805c-eaab16fe1df5"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14881628,"exerciseName":"2","page":631,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"f6e61495-0a6a-4bb3-beb9-d4f893ac05a5","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-18-critical-thinking-questions-2-f6e61495-0a6a-4bb3-beb9-d4f893ac05a5"},{"id":14881627,"exerciseName":"1","page":630,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"85cd7418-f1a7-4867-ba24-c45a7e5dc698","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-18-critical-thinking-questions-1-85cd7418-f1a7-4867-ba24-c45a7e5dc698"}],"_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-18-critical-thinking-questions-3-8d3fc3a8-18d9-4e38-bf8e-94074f7deb3c"}